<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Minister on Challenges Facing Govt in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Finance Minister
Herbert Murerwa said the government's biggest challenge in 1997
is to reduce the high unemployment rate, indigenise the economy
and redress the land imbalance.
</P>
<P>
At a New Year's Eve party, Murerwa called on indigenous groups
to work together for the indigenous programme to work, the
Zimbabwe National News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Indigenisation is going to be the government's priority in
1997," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Murerwa said the Zimbabwean government is committed to the
indigenisation program but cannot do it alone. "There is a need
for networking among indigenous groups. We must have a national
outlook to indigenisation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that the blacks and whites in Zimbabwe
should work together towards indigenising the economy.
</P>
<P>
Other challenges the government will be facing include job
creation and the land issue, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's unemployment rate currently stood at 50 percent,
which was worsened by more than 300,000 school leavers entering
the job market each year when only 20,000 jobs are created
annually.
</P>
<P>
Murerwa said 1996 was a "momentous year" because of good rains
which contributed to an economic growth of 8 percent and the
reduction of inflation from 26 percent to 13 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
