<HEADLINE> Zambia's Debt Service Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's external debt service
ratio had declined to 21 percent of the country's gross domestic
product (gdp) by the end of November 1996, down from 56 percent
of the same period in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
This was achieved despite the withdrawal of balance of payment
support by some donor countries who were not pleased with
political developments in the country, according to the Ministry
of Finance and Economic Development today.
</P>
<P>
It signifies the government's adherence to the policy of debt
reduction to a manageable ratio so as to depend less on donors.
</P>
<P>
Zambia spend 153 million U.S. Dollars on debt service between
January and October 1996, according to the latest issue of
"Zambia Fortnightly Statistics" published by the Bank of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The country's external debt has grown from 654 million U.S.
Dollars in 1970 to 7.2 billion U.S. Dollars in 1991 and then
declined to 6.6 billion U.S. Dollars in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
