<HEADLINE> Nigerian Cabinet Due To Be Reshuffled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's two-year-old military
cabinet at the head of state General Sani Abacha's beck and call
is likely to be reshuffled earlier this year, the local
"Guardian" newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Less than half of all the 36 cabinet ministers could remain
their posts, the report quoted presidential sources as saying,
adding that ministers who have introduced reforms to make
government more popular are expected to retain.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, few ministers will be retained on
their current posts, some will be reassigned and many dropped.
</P>
<P>
It would be the second reshuffle by Abacha since he took
office on November 17, 1993. The first took place in March 1995.
</P>
<P>
The move is said to aim to strengthen the federal
"administrative machinery as the transition program gets to its
critical stage."
</P>
<P>
However, the time table is still undecided, partly because the
1997 state budget is yet to be made public, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
The military government reappointed all the 30 state
administrators in August, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Five opposition parties registered in last October called, in
a statement late December, on Abacha to curb official
meddlesomeness in state politics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
