<HEADLINE> New York State Hospitals Start Open Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Hospitals in New York State
will start open competition under a new law which takes effect as
of today.
</P>
<P>
The new law lifts price controls on hospitals and forces them
to compete in an increasingly cutthroat health care market,
according to a New York Times report today.
</P>
<P>
The report described the change in the medical system as one of
"the most turbulent ever." "No state has ever undergone this level
of deregulation before," an expert said.
</P>
<P>
For the last 15 years, state regulators have fixed what
hospitals could charge the insurers and health maintenance
organizations that send them patients, a system that critics said
removed the incentives for hospitals to hold down costs.
</P>
<P>
Under the new law, every hospital and insurer in New York is
free to negotiate their own deals. For hospitals and insurers
accustomed to the security of fixed rates, it has been a bit like
learning to swim by being dumped into strange swirling seas, the
newspaper commented.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is for insurance rates to come down and for hospitals
to be healthier and more self-reliant," Dr. Barbara DeBuono, the
New York State Commissioner of Health, was quoted as saying. "I
think this will be a much healthier industry in the long run. But
I'm frank about there being bumps in the road at the beginning,"
DeBuono added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
