<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Denounces Israeli Soldier's Shootings in West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government today
expressed shock at an Israeli soldier's shootings in the West
Bank, and a White House spokeswoman said President Bill Clinton
called Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to express condolences.
</P>
<P>
"The president is outraged and saddened by this morning's
incident in Hebron," according to an AP report quoting deputy
White House press secretary Mary Ellen Glynn at Hilton Head
Island, South Carolina state.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that an Israeli soldier armed with an M16
automatic rifle opened fire on Palestinians in Hebron's
marketplace, during which at least 11 Palestinians were wounded.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman noted President Clinton called Arafat, but did
not speak with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. She said
the U.S. envoy in the region, Dennis Ross, had met with Netanyahu
after the shooting and was expected to meet with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was briefed on the West Bank shootings before he left
the beach home on Hilton Head Island.
</P>
<P>
"The president condemns this cowardly act, which was clearly
designed to make it more difficult to conclude an agreement on
Israeli deployment from Hebron," the spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
"The best answer to this action would be for the two sides to
close the remaining gaps and move forward with the hard work of
forging a durable peace between Israelis and Palestinians," she
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
