<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Condemns Terrorist Shooting, Calling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- To offset repercussions of
the terrorist shooting today, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu strongly condemned the incident while calling for calm
and continuation of peace process.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today after an Israeli soldier shot and wounded 6
Palestinians in a central Hebron market, Netanyahu phoned
Palestinian Authority (PA) President Yasser Arafat to express
his regrets and condemnation of the "criminal act."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference, Netanyahu once again clearly
condemned this terrorist attack. "We condemn it, we repudiate it
completely this despicable crime," he said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu called on both Israelis and Palestinians to act
with restraint and responsibility to avoid escalating the
tension. He said Israel was doing whatever possible to restore
the law and order in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Tension in Hebron is running high today and dozens of
Palestinians threw stones at Israeli soldiers near the hospital
in Hebron where the wounded received treatment. Israel feared
the retaliation by Palestinian extremists.
</P>
<P>
Denouncing those who attempted to derail Israeli troop
pullback from Hebron, Netanyahu reiterated the importance of
securing speedy conclusion of a Hebron agreement. "No crime can
stop us from doing so," he said.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the day, Netanyahu has held several consulations
with cabinet ministers and security heads on offsetting the
negative effects of today's shooting on the nearly-concluded
Hebron agreement.
</P>
<P>
Both Israeli Defense Minister Mordechai and Army Chief of
Staff Lipkin Shahak today toured Hebron, which has been under
curfew imposed by Israeli troops. Mordechai also met with
Palestinian Hebron Mayor Mustafa Natsche to discuss the
situation.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai promised Israel would continue talks with the PA to
wrap up the Hebron agreement. "I hope, in a very short time, we
will complete the negotiations, and after we signed the
agreement, the army will be redeployed in a very short time," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Fearing the Palestinian side could tough its demand in Hebron
talks after the terrorist incident, the Israeli government also
made it clear that it would make no new concessions. One
remaining dispute blocking a deal was Israel's objection to
Palestinian demand for joint security patrols near the Tomb of
Patriachs, the holy shrine for both Jews and Arabs.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister's Office said Netanyahu had told Arafat
that terrorist crimes were committed by both Israelis and
Palestinians, so the PA should not use this as excuse to force
Israel to make more concessions.
</P>
<P>
U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross today conveyed a message from
U.S. President Bill Clinton to express shock and dismay over the
terrorist act and call on both sides to push forward the peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
Ross went to Gaza to meet with Arafat late today after
holding consulations with Netanyahu and other Israeli officials
in a bid to find ways to conclude the much-waited Hebron
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Ross is striving to arrange an Arafat-Netanyahu summit to
initial the Hebron deal. Meanwhile, Palestinian negotiators
delayed today's talks on Hebron due to the shooting, but they
said the negotiations could possibly resume tonight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
