<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Engineering Industry Likely to Lose 400,000 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Britain's engineering industry is
likely to lose up to 400,000 jobs over the next decade through
technological and product change, according to a forecast by the
Engineering Employers' Federation.
</P>
<P>
The forecast, which is due to be published later this month,
will reveal the results a long-term strategic review of the future
of the engineering industry across the country.
</P>
<P>
Based on an extensive survey of engineering company chief
executives and training job development professionals, the
forecast will focus on the shape of the engineering industry until
the year 2010, steering clear of business changes resulting from
the economic cycle.
</P>
<P>
In overall terms, the review will suggest that the prospects
for engineering in Britain look reasonably optimistic and the
country is likely to focus increasingly on the higher-value
computer-based control and systems products rather than
traditional metal-bashing.
</P>
<P>
The review is to predict a decline in Britain's engineering
workforce from its current level of about 1.6 million people to
1.2 million, a cut of 400,000 jobs by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The profile of the remaining engineering workforce will change
significantly with a sharp reduction in the number of unskilled
and semi-skilled jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
