<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Government Urged To Protect Wildlife </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Wildlife
Protection Organization today urged the government to formulate
policies and issue regulations to protect wildlives in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The organization's Manager Gebremarkos Woldeselasse said lives
of certain animals are endangered as their habitats are being
converted to agricultural and ranch lands.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''menelik'' bushbuck, nyala, wallia, red fox, zebra
and korke are among the rare animals whose very existance is
endangered. Twenty-one mamals, 17 bird species and two
invertebrates endemic to Ethiopia are now threatened to the point
of extinction.
</P>
<P>
The present land allotment in Abayata Shala, Awash, Babile,
Omo, Mago and other parks is damaging the ecology, in addition to
posing a threat to the lives of the animals, the manager said.
</P>
<P>
Woldeselasse stressed that these invaluable and rare wildlives
will disappear in a short span of time unless the government
urgently formulate policies and issue regulations to protect
them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
