<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll of PKK Rebels Rises to 72 in Turkey's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The death toll of the rebels of
the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) has risen to 72 in the
cross-border operations by Turkish security forces in northern
Iraq in the past two days, according to an army statement today.
</P>
<P>
The statement issued by the General Staff of the Turkish Armed
Forces said that the Turkish Armed Forces have been continuing
the cross-border military operations in northern Iraq despite the
bad weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the Turkish security forces killed
eight PKK rebels in Nusaybin town in Mardin province bordering
Syria and captured three rebels including two Syrian nationals,
said the semi-official Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Turkish F-4 fighters taking off from the air base in
Diyarbakir, southeastern Turkey, had bombarded three PKK camps in
Sinath region, 10 kilometers deep into northern Iraq early this
morning in the cross-border operations which started Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
About 5,000 Turkish troops and village guards attacked the
PKK militants who tried to flee from Sindi throat in northern
Iraq following the bombardment of the Cobra helicopters.
</P>
<P>
Turkish troops have entered into northern Iraq for several
times in attempts to destroy the military bases from where the
PKK guerrillas launch cross-border raids against Turkish military
and civilian targets.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government, which has been deprived of the control
over northern Kurdish area by the allied forces, has made
protests against the Turkish operations before, accusing Turkey
of violation of its sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Turkish security forces have killed 13,255 rebels, wounded 244
and captured about 2,000 since August 1984 when the PKK started a
guerrilla war for more autonomy in southeastern Turkey, according
to official figures.
</P>
<P>
Over 21,000 people including PKK rebels, civilians and
government troops have been killed in the conflicts in the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
