<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Starts to Register Internet Clients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Internet today began to
register its clients in Ethiopia, according to the country's
newly established Internet Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Head of the bureau Fanta Adane told local journalists that the
Internet electronic appliance in the country has the capacity to
serve at least 5,000 clients.
</P>
<P>
He added that Internet would enable clients to get access to
necessary information across the world at low prices.
</P>
<P>
Internet will enable individuals, enterprises and government
institutions to exchange written documents, computer files, news
stories and opinions within the network of the International
Computers Federation and make advertisements which could get
through within seconds, he said.
</P>
<P>
It costs only 23 seconds to get a piece of information from
Canada through Internet while the time to receive information
from European and Asian countries is even shorter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
