<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Import Tax Harmonized Between Tanzania Mainland, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania Union and
Isles governments have harmonized import tax for five key
commodities effective today.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued here today by Acting Minister for Finance
Daniel Yona listed the commodities as rice, wheat flour, sugar,
cooking oil and Khanga.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the move is designed to plug loopholes
for tax evasion through the Zanzibar Isles route and expected to
strengthen the revenue position of the two governments.
</P>
<P>
The Zanzibar route had been a controversial subject for
several years, with claims that the union government was losing
at least 6 billion Tanzania Shillings (about 10 million U.S.
Dollars) a month in revenue through tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
The statement said, however, that new rates to be applied will
be announced shortly.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the rates will be worked out in a manner that is
going to minimize adverse effects on consumer prices and revenue
position for any of the two governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
