<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Outgoing UN Chief Returns Home Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Outgoing U.N. Secretary General
Boutros Boutros Ghali will return home Friday after finishing a
five-year term at the helm of the world body, with
Undersecretary-General Kofi Annan of Ghana replacing him today.
</P>
<P>
Ghali's expected 10-year reign was cut in half after his
renomination for a second five-year term was vetoed by the U.S.,
while the other 14 members of the Security Council supported him.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who has been working with the world body for 30 years
and is the first U.N. chief to assume the office from inside,
promised to make the United Nations more open and work to resolve
all its financial problems.
</P>
<P>
Ghali, who once said "the member states still don't know what
role they want from the U.N.," only wished "good luck to the
U.N. and happy new year" on New Year's eve, also his last day in
office.
</P>
<P>
He is going to put final touches on his book on the
Egyptian-Israeli peace negotiations and the peace initiative in
November 1977.
</P>
<P>
For someone born in a 100-room Cairo palace and accustomed to
a starring role in the diplomatic circle, this marks an abrupt
end to an illustrious career.
</P>
<P>
When U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher proposed a
one-year extension earlier 1996, the Egyptian reportedly rebuffed
it by asking whether he was being offered "a tip."
</P>
<P>
His grandfather, former Prime Minister Boutros Pasha Ghali,
was assassinated in 1910 when Britain was Egypt's colonial ruler.
</P>
<P>
Ghali held the rank of deputy prime minister for foreign
affairs in 1991 after more than 13 years as minister of state for
foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
He accompanied the late President Anwar Sadat on his historic
trip to Jerusalem in 1977. He then played a key role at the Camp
David talks that led to the 1979 peace treaty between Egypt and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Ghali became embroiled in a well-publicized row with the
Security Council after six months on the job when he complained
that too much was being spent on U.N. peacekeeping in Bosnia and
too little to assist starvation-stricken Somalia.
</P>
<P>
To Africa, he said, Yugoslavia appeared to be "the war of the
rich."
</P>
<P>
Despite U.S. criticism, he is widely credited with having done
more to streamline the organization than most of his predecessors.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. was owed more than 2 billion U.S. dollars in unpaid
budget dues and peacekeeping costs, more than half of it by the
United States. This is part of the reason behind his dismissal by
the U.S. administration.
</P>
<P>
He was the first secretary-general appointed in the post-Cold
War era. The U.N. mounted 26 operations between 1989 and 1996,
compared with 15 relatively simple monitoring missions during the
previous 40 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
