<HEADLINE> Crime Rate on Increase in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Crime rate in Tanzania
has increased by nearly six percent, a statement by the Inspector
General of Police (IGP) Omar Mahita said here today.
</P>
<P>
According to a report signed by Commissioner of Police W.
Mwansasu on behalf of the IGP, there were 238,200 reported crimes
in the country between January and June last year, compared to
225,017 reported cases in the same period of 1995.
</P>
<P>
"There have been 13,183 more crimes, which represents a 5.8
percent increase," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The IGP warned in the statement against the habit of setting
on fire people suspected to have committed crimes, saying that
such acts are illegal and punishable by law.
</P>
<P>
"The police would like to remind people to abide by the laws
of the land. When suspects are caught, they should be sent to the
police and let the law take its course," the statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
