<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suleymanoglu Announces Retirement from Weightlifting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Naim Suleymanoglu of Turkey, who
won three Olympic gold medals in his career, announced his
retirement on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"I am now 30. It is enough. I am announcing that I am putting
an end to my sports life," Suleymanoglu was quoted by Turkey's
Milliyet newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"Weightlifting has given me a lot, and it has given me a lot of
joy," said Suleymanoglu, who is only 1.49 meters tall and named
"Pocket Hercules" by his fans.
</P>
<P>
He told Milliyet that he had thought of Sydney Olympics in 2000
as his next target, but decided that he could not remain in active
weightlifting for four more years.
</P>
<P>
Suleymanoglu said he would working in weightlifting as
technical director or manager after his retirement.
</P>
<P>
He was elected "sports personality of the year" for the sixth
consecutive year in a poll organized by Milliyet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
