<HEADLINE> Flights Delayed In Northeast China Because Of Snow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, January 2 (Xinhua) -- A snowstorm that hit northeast
China's Liaoning Province in the past two days has delayed flights
and temporarily halted railway and highway traffic.
</P>
<P>
Seven flights of Shenyang's North China Airlines could still
not return as late as 6:00 P.M. today, and other flights at
Shenyang's Taoxian International Airport were delayed, a spokesman
of the Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC) told Xinhua
in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Heavy snow also delayed other planes bound for major
northeastern cities, he said, but that the situation should
improve if the bad weather does not last.
</P>
<P>
Railway traffic in Liaoning, which was temporarily disrupted,
has returned to normal, according to the Shenyang Railway Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The snowstorm that began New Year's eve was said to be the
biggest in three years, and brought temperatures down to 17
degrees below zero centigrade.
</P>
<P>
In Shenyang, Anshan, and other cities, traffic police braved
bitter cold to direct traffic, while students and residents took
to the streets to scrape away snow and ice.
</P>
<P>
The power, heat, and gas departments and vegetable suppliers
were working overtime to guarantee the safety and wellbeing of
residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
