<HEADLINE> Hebron Remains Quiet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Hebron is reportedly quiet
today, one day after an Israeli soldier opened fire to a crowd of
Palestinians in the center of the West Bank town, wounding at
least seven people.
</P>
<P>
Israeli forces have beefed up the security in Hebron, as
armored personnel carriers were placed at key points around the
city, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Noam Friedman, the soldier who carried out the
attack Wednesday, remained in custody, as police and the
General Security Services are trying to find out more about
the man and the motive of his actions.
</P>
<P>
Israeli media revealed that Friedman had mental problems.
</P>
<P>
Friedman joined army several months ago, and after some basic
training, he was assigned to a guarding unit at an army base on
the outskirts of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The oldest of four children, Friedman lived with his parents in
the Jewish settlement town of Ma'aleh Adumim north of
Jerusalem. He returns home every evening from his base except when
on duty.
</P>
<P>
From a Jewish family, Friedman studied, before his eventually
call-up to the army, in a number of Yeshivas, Jewish religious
seminaries, in the Jerusalem area.
</P>
<P>
Press reports today quoted several rabbis, or Jewish priests,
and people who know him, as saying that Friedman had shown strange
behaviors for some years.
</P>
<P>
A psychologist at Ma'aleh Adumim, who treated him, reportedly
sent a letter to the army, suggesting serious consideration on
Friedman's enlisting and entitlement to carrying weapon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli army's military police have also been ordered to open
investigations into Friedman, particularly into the circumstances
of his call up into the army. 
</P>
</TEXT>
