<DOCNO> XIE19970102.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Hiked Fertilizer Prices Worry Zambian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Wang Nengbiao)
</P>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Farmers and farm union officials
across Zambia are complaining about the increased fertilizer
prices, which they said could lead a food shortage in the new
year.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Zambian Agricultural Ministry raised the
fertilizer prices for the 1996-97 season from the previous
equivalent of 15 U.S. Dollars and 16 U.S. Dollars for a
50-kilogram bag of basal and top dressing fertilizer respectively
to 23 U.S. Dollars and 38 U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Prices are varying from district to district and are also
lower for cash transactions and higher on credit.
</P>
<P>
Farmers across the country are concerned over the hiked prices
as well as the absence of fertilizers in some places.
</P>
<P>
In Chibombo, central Zambia, they said about 100 hectares of
maize may go to waste due to the lack of fertilizer, blaming it
on the government's failure to deliver fertilizer and provide
credit facilities on time.
</P>
<P>
A government official described the problem as a disaster
because the majority of farmers simply don't have money to buy
the fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
He added that even those with money but living in remote areas
are unable to secure fertilizer because it is mainly found on the
black market in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Another official from a farmers' association said farmers
could not afford fertilizer at the new prices, warning that there
will be a terrible fall in maize production this year.
</P>
<P>
"There is an urgent need for the government to review their
policy," said the official.
</P>
<P>
The same concern was raised by Zambia National Farmers Union,
noting that in some places, farmers have abandoned maize growing
because of lack of fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government attributed the high prices to the
depreciation of the local currency, Kwacha.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister of Agriculture Ackson Sejani rebuked the
farming community for complaining at the new fertilizer prices,
telling them to diversify farming if maize production is an
expensive venture.
</P>
<P>
"Farmers are very slow to grasp that. If it doesn't make
economic sense to plant maize they could just plant enough to
feed the family or change to other crops like soya beans and
cotton which are fast selling," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sejani said his ministry will hold a meeting later this month
with all farmers' unions and associations, private importers and
other stake holders to iron out the fertilizer issue and work out
a sustainable credit scheme. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970102.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
