<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Needs to Reduce Budget Deficit: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan should reduce its
budget deficit to at least 3 percent of its gross domestic product
(GDP) to ensure sustained socio-economic growth, a high Pakistani
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"We can live with a budget deficit of 3 percent and anything
more than that will create problems," Shahid Burki, the prime
minister's advisor on finance and economic affairs, told the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) asked Pakistan to reduce
its budget deficit to 4 percent of the GDP if it wants to get
loans from the fund.
</P>
<P>
Burki said the government has to get loans from IMF under
certain conditions, because the choice is to get them or go
bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
He said that in Pakistan, the tax elasticity is only 0.88 and
the government has to have a tax base which expands by bringing
new items and people under the tax net.
</P>
<P>
"We would have to have the political courage to tax agriculture
to help close the resource gap, besides taxing retail trade,
transport and small industry," he said.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural production, which makes up 25 percent of the GDP,
contributes little to the revenue as successive governments did
not take strong measures to ask big landlords to pay taxes.
</P>
<P>
Burki said the government is following a three-pronged strategy
to stabilize the economy by making structural changes, alleviating
poverty and improving human resources.
</P>
<P>
He said that if the government keeps postponing tough decisions
in regard to structural changes, the country will have to go
through an economic crisis after every two to three years.
</P>
<P>
After coming to power on November 5 last year, the caretaker
government set economic reforms as one of its top priorities.
</P>
<P>
A number of economic reform measures have been announced to
restructure banking and other economic sectors and realize
macro-economic stabilization.
</P>
<P>
Bank borrowing for budget support has been reduced by 12
billion rupees (300 million U.S. dollars) since the caretaker
government took office.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970102.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Literacy Rate Increases to 39 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's literacy rate has
increased from 35 percent in 1991 to 39 percent in 1995-96, says a
survey presented here today.
</P>
<P>
The report on the Pakistan Integrated Household Survey (PIHS)
presented by the Federal Bureau of Statistics (FBS) said the
percentage of the population over 10 years of age attending school
increased from 47 percent in 1991 to 52 percent in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
Gross enrollment in primary schools stands at 74 percent in
1995-96, virtually no change since 1991.
</P>
<P>
Net enrollment in primary schools fell slightly from 46 percent
in 1991 to 44 percent in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
Girls primary enrollment as a percentage of total enrollment
rose from 39 percent in 1991 to 42 percent in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
Some 16 percent of children left school before completing
primary education, not much change from that of 1991.
</P>
<P>
Student-teacher ratio is 30 students per teacher in girls' and
34 in boys' schools.
</P>
<P>
The report on the PIHS contains information on basic education,
primary health, population welfare and rural water supply and
sanitation.
</P>
<P>
The survey covers about 12,800 households from which data have
been collected on a number of different topics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
