<HEADLINE> Pakistan Probably to Reopen Embassy in Kabul: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan will probably reopen
its embassy in Kabul, a Pakistani Foreign Office spokesman said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a weekly briefing at the Foreign Office, the
spokesman said that Pakistan technically has the embassy in Kabul
but the premises were damaged in the past.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan closed down its embassy in Kabul soon after September
6, 1995, when thousands of protesters destroyed the embassay,
accusing Pakistan of supporting the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
However, the Pakistani government has been denying such
allegations and reiterating its neutrality in the Afghan conflict.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said at the briefing that Pakistan has not
formally recognized the Taliban regime in Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's dealing with the ousted Afghan government led by
Burhanuddin Rabbani had come to an end because Rabbani had no more
authority in Kabul, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Local press reported today that Pakistan is planning to reopen
its embassy in Kabul in the near future and will become the first
country to have a diplomatic presence in the Afghan capital which
fell to the Taliban on September 27, 1996.  
</P>
