<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Develops First Tourist Guide Robot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Scientists from the Robot
Research Institute of Harbin Polytechnical University have
developed China's first robot that performs the duties of a
tourist guide.
</P>
<P>
The robot, which looks like a short spaceman, is 1.1 meters
tall and weighs 17 kilograms, and travels 120 cm per second,
according to Science and Technology Daily.
</P>
<P>
It speaks several languages, including Chinese, English,
Russian and Japanese, and can identify tourist spots with the help
of a sort of radar, an infrared sensor, and a photoelectric switch
in its head.
</P>
<P>
If someone is in the robot's path, he can say, "Please get out
of the way," and after the person moves he is always careful to
say "thank you."
</P>
<P>
If he encounters a barrier, he makes a detour.
</P>
<P>
According to professor Wang Shuguo, one of the robot's
inventors, it can act as a tourist guide, a shopping guide, or do
work for commercial or service departments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
