<TEXT>
<P>
Shanghai, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Sales of computers in Shanghai,
China's largest economic center, reached six billion yuan in 1996,
up 50 percent over the previous year, and this year are expected
to reach 9 billion yuan, according to the Shanghai municipal
office in charge of the computer industry.
</P>
<P>
"Shanghai Science and Technology Review" attributes the growth
to business reforms and imports of advanced foreign technology.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Yangtze River Computer Group became the first
among the city's computer groups to top one billion yuan in output
value in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's software enterprises have concentrated on developing
software, intergrated systems, and computer networks, and sales
in 1996 were estimated at one billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
A number of international corporations such as IBM, INTEL, HP,
Philips, and NEC have invested in Shanghai, and the city's Gold
Card Project is using a computer network that connects 80 percent
of the city's banks.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 ATMs have been installed, with 900 of them
already in operation.
</P>
<P>
More than six percent of the urban families have personal
computers, and the municipal government is planning on getting the
computer industry to be its new backbone industry. 
</P>
