<HEADLINE> Palace Complex Of Chinese Peasant Leader Restored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The palace complex of a peasant
uprising leader in the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) has been restored
in Suzhou city, in east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The Zhongwangfu (Palace of the Prince of Loyalty), belonged to
Li Xiucheng, a famous general of the Heavenly Kingdom (1851-1864),
was established after the Taiping Rebellion, the largest peasant
uprisings in Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
The palace complex was seriously damaged by weather over the
past century and some parts were in need of repairs before
conservation work started last September.
</P>
<P>
The conservation project followed state guidelines that say
that restored historical buildings should be faithful to the
original.
</P>
