JAKARTA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh started his two-day visit to Indonesia to strengthen
trade and investment ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit, who arrived here at noon for his first overseas visit
since he was appointed prime minister on December 1, held brief
talks with Indonesian President Soeharto, State Secretary
Moerdiono told the press.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry sources said that Chavalit's visit to
Indonesia "is basically a courtesy call," a tradition for new
leaders in the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
members to call on fellow ASEAN leaders shortly after taking
office.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a Thai diplomatic source said, "they (Soeharto and
Chavalit) will have an open-ended discussion as there are no
particular issues to take up."
</P>
<P>
Investments in communications, mining and fisheries will be
among the topics of their discussions, official sources here said
earlier.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders are scheduled to hold formal talks Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
A state banquet will be held in honor of the Thai prime
minister later in the evening.  
</P>
</TEXT>
