<HEADLINE> Computerized Ship Ticketing Now Available in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Computerized reservations for
Yangtze River trips, officially went into operation on December
29, in China.
</P>
<P>
The system was designed by the Yangtze River Shipping Group,
the country's biggest inland water passenger carrier, with an
investment of more than eight million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The computer system means that it takes only one minute to get
a ticket, compared with some 10 minutes in the old manual system.
</P>
<P>
Three major ports, Yichang, Nanjing, and Shanghai, have joined
the network, and 22 other large and medium-sized ones are
scheduled to join the network this year.
</P>
<P>
Passengers will be able to buy tickets at any of the 25
harbors, and can book tickets one month in advance, including
round-trip tickets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
