<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Patrol Boat Donated by China Called Into Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leonean President Tejan
Kabbah today commissioned into service a patrol gunboat granted
by China, saying it would "minimise the high rate of poaching in
Freetown's territorial waters by foreign vessels."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Kabbah said the aid reflected the
"strong ties of friendship" between China and the West African
state.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ambassador to Sierra Leone Qu Weming said it is
important for Sierra Leone "to patrol its territorial waters in
terms of security and the conservation of valuable foreign
exchange."
</P>
<P>
Officials in Freetown said the boat, worth three million U.S.
Dollars and able to carry up to 200 security personnel, was part
of a 20 million U.S. Dollar assistance provided by China after a
high level delegation from Freetown visited Beijing in 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics released by the World Bank, Sierra
Leone is losing over 30 million U.S. Dollars annually as a result
of poaching by foreign vessels.
</P>
<P>
Eight years ago, Beijing had already donated a patrol boat to
Sierra Leone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
