<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Capital Market to be Bull in 1997: MIA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Investors'
Association (MIA) said today the local stock market is expected to
"steam" ahead for a further gain in 1997.
</P>
<P>
That the excess liquidity, the biggest driving force in any
financial market, amounted to 2.4 billion ringgit (about 960
million U.S. dollars) as at the end of August 1996, was good for
the capital market, MIA president PHS Lim said in a statement here
today.
</P>
<P>
"There is an even chance to see a favorable stock market for
Malaysia in 1997 especially during the first half (of 1997) due to
various factors," he said, adding the targeted 8.3 percent
economic growth rate for 1997 should augur well for the Malaysian
stock market.
</P>
<P>
He said the fear of an overheating Malaysian economy was over,
hence those foreign institutional investors who once harbored the
fear of an over-heating economy with high inflation and high
interest rates should greatly welcome the Malaysian capital market
now.
</P>
<P>
Money supply in terms of M3 for the month of November 1996 was
21.7 percent, Lim said.
</P>
<P>
He said another factor to fuel the local capital markets was
the balance of payments where Malaysia's merchandise account was
expected to register a large surplus in 1997 with higher exports.
</P>
<P>
Lim said the national bank could employ a tight monetary policy
at this juncture to stabilize interest rates. "On a long term
basis, interest rates will decline as the government may not use
such policy to combat inflation," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the bank would mop up excess liquidity in the
market via more issues of unit trust funds.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing, construction and services sectors are
expected to perform satisfactorily in 1997 along with industries
such as stock broking, banking, gambling, health care and
medication, and transportation, according to Lim.
</P>
<P>
He said the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) main board may
see a growth of about 20 percent during the first half of 1997 to
beyond 1,300 points for the KLSE Composite Index.
</P>
<P>
The second board may undergo corrections from time to time but
"we expect it to outperform the main board for the rest of 1997,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"There will be rotational plays in 1997, and some stocks may
appreciate sharply and we may see more takeovers in the second
board companies," he added.
</P>
<P>
Lim also disclosed a new fund amounting to 500 million ringgit
(about 200 million U.S. dollars) would be set up by an
international financial institution with a local investment house
to invest in small and medium paid up capital companies listed in
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
"Second board stock prices are very volatile and investors who
wish to invest in such stocks must have financial holding power,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
On market capitalization, Lim said, "Our market capitalization
may even exceed 1 trillion ringgit (about 400 billion U.S.
dollars) within three to four years." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
