<HEADLINE> Muslim Rebels Ask for Transparent Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) has asked that the forthcoming peace negotiations with the
government be open to the public, the Philippine News Agency (PNA)
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The request was among several conditions set by the MILF to
avoid speculation about what will be discussed during the formal
negotiations set to start next week, the PNA said.
</P>
<P>
The respective technical committees of the government and the
MILF are slated to meet on January 7 to work out the talking
points prior to the formal peace negotiations at the Dawah Center
in Sultan Kudarat Town, Maguindanao.
</P>
<P>
Also sought by the MILF is the absence of armed security men,
whether MILF or government, at the venue of the negotiations.
There should be no armed men at the peace talks venue, the MILF
urged.
</P>
<P>
Al Haj Murad, MILF vice chair for military affairs, earlier
said only local cops of the Sultan Kudarat Town police force will
be allowed to provide security for the peace talks site.
</P>
<P>
"We do not need an elaborate security plan. The town's police
force is already good enough to secure the negotiators," Murad
said.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the government negotiating panel, however,
remained silent on the MILF's request on security.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Murad said the coming fasting month of Ramadan
should not be seen as a hindrance to the conduct of the peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Muslim faithfuls will observe a month-long fast from January 10
to February 10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
