<HEADLINE> HK Listed Chinese Stocks Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese companies listed on
the Hong Kong Stock Exchange today enjoyed a sharp rise on the
first trading day this year, with the Hang Seng China Enterprises
Index surging 58.05 points or 5.92 percent to 1,038.60.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time in 16 months that Hong Kong-listed Chinese
stocks have exceeded the 1,000-point base.
</P>
<P>
This came in contrast to the general atmosphere of the Hong
Kong Stock Exchange which plunged sharply today, with the Hang
Seng Index falling 248 points or 1.84 percent to close at 13,203.
</P>
<P>
Local stock experts held that the market was dragged down by
the Wall Street stocks which lost over 100 points on the last
trading day of 1996, but they gave optimistic forecasts about the
medium- and long-term prospects of the market.
</P>
<P>
They believed the correction was quite reasonable after strong
gains in the past few months. There should not be any worries
about it, they said.
</P>
<P>
Among major sub-indices of Hang Seng Index, properties dropped
dramatically 512 points, while finance lost 216 points, commerce
and industry fell 198 points and utilities decreased 184 points.
</P>
<P>
Today's turnover reached 10.089 billion HK dollars (1.29
billion US dollars), compared with that of 9.783 billion HK
dollars (1.25 billion US dollars) on the last full trading day.
</P>
</TEXT>
