<HEADLINE> Normal Rail Traffic Resumes in India's Assam State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The railway track, damaged by
the explosion on the Brahmaputra Mail near Korajhar District in
Assam State, eastern India, Monday night, has been repaired and
normal rail traffic has resumed, official sources said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Normal traffic was restored last night within 48 hours of the
bombing suspected to have been carried out by the local militants,
the Indian Railway Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
In all, 33 people were killed and 49 others injured in the
blast. "As the debris have been cleared and the search operation
is over, there is no possibility of recovery of any more dead
body," the ministry said. Earlier reports put the death toll at
300.
</P>
<P>
On the request of Assam Chief Minister Prafulla Kumar Mahanta,
Railway Minister Ram Vilas Paswan has ordered that one battalion
of the Railway Protection Force be immediately deployed in that
region to secure the railway tracks and other installations. An
additional company has already been sent there.  
</P>
</TEXT>
