<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Firm to Take 50 Pc Stake in S. African Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Killinghall
Corporation (KMB) will take a 50 percent stake in Southern Bank of
Africa Investment Holdings Ltd. (SBAIH), it was announced here
today.
</P>
<P>
KMB said in a statement that its investment in Southern Bank of
Africa Ltd. (SBA) through SBAIH will be funded by an off-shore
bank borrowing in U.S. dollars equivalent to Rand 50 million (12
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
KMB said the investment in SBAIH was in line with the company's
objective to invest in the financial sector, both locally and
overseas, and the investment was expected to enhance and diversify
the company's future earnings.
</P>
<P>
SBA will be a wholly-owned subsidiary of SBAIH which will be
incorporated in South Africa in the first quarter of 1997 with an
authorized share capital of Rand 100 million (24 million U.S.
dollars) comprising 100 million shares of Rand 1.00 each, KMB
said.
</P>
<P>
The first branch will be in Johannesburg and will provide a
wide range of financial services focusing primarily among others
in intermediation in the middle markets, trade financing and
project financing.
</P>
<P>
KMB also said approval had been granted by The Reserve Bank of
South Africa on September 3, 1996 for SBA to operate as a
universal bank in South Africa. 
</P>
