<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thailand Sets Higher Goals for Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's tourism industry is
setting higher goals for 1997 with a focus on the exploration of
more new markets and special interest events after it has gained a
strong momentum during the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The Tourism Authority of Thailand (TAT) recently introduced its
marketing plans for the new year, saying Thailand will strive to
attract at least 7.84 million tourist arrivals in the year, 7.4
percent higher than the estimated figure for 1996.
</P>
<P>
The TAT also set a target for the country's tourism industry to
earn 9.6 billion U.S. dollars in foreign exchange this year, up 11
percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Thai tourism industry has gained a strong momentum during
the past two years when the country held a historic celebration of
King Bhumibol Adulyadej's golden jubilee.
</P>
<P>
The TAT planned to attract at least 7.2 million tourist
arrivals and earn about 8 billion dollars in 1996, but the actual
figures for the year are expected to be slightly higher.
</P>
<P>
During the past year, most of Thailand's tourism promotion
activities were launched around the core event of marking the 50th
anniversary of the king's ascension to the throne and the TAT
mainly aimed to attract tourists aged over 50, honeymoon couples
and four-member families.
</P>
<P>
This year, the TAT has made some changes in its tourism
promotion strategies, in particular by focusing more on female
tourists while continuing to consolidate its achievements over the
past year.
</P>
<P>
Outlining the TAT's marketing plans for the new year, TAT
Governor Seree Angpaichitr said the efforts will be directed at
promoting the image of Thailand as a safe and high-quality tourist
destination with a great diversity of attractions.
</P>
<P>
In terms of profile targets, Thailand is to put the maximum
emphasis on attracting female tourists as it believes that females
throughout the world have shown an increasing propensity for
travel and they play a growing role in making decisions in regard
to travel, he said.
</P>
<P>
Promoting visits to Thailand by female tourists will also help
correct the negative image of sex tourism, the senior Thai tourism
official said.
</P>
<P>
Attracting honeymooners to Thailand, especially from Japan and
South Korea, is another target set by the TAT to help promote the
image of Thailand as a quality, safe and impressive tourist
destination, Seree said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the TAT this year will continue to make efforts to
attract elderly visitors, family groups, young travel fans and
Thais residing overseas.
</P>
<P>
Thailand this year will pay more attention to regional tourism
cooperation programs in the greater Mekong subregion and the
Indonesia-Malaysia-Thailand growth triangle.
</P>
<P>
The TAT has set up the Agency for Coordinating Mekong Tourism
Activities in Bangkok this year. The new agency will effectively
become a secretariat for the Working Group on the Greater Mekong
Subregion Tourism Sector, which comprises representatives from
Cambodia, China, Laos, Myanmar, Thailand, Vietnam and
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
East European countries and Russia are also among the new
markets  the TAT plans to develop this year as it sees a good
potential for tourism development there.
</P>
<P>
On the special interest segment, the main focus will be on
frequent and experienced visitors who tend to tour Thailand for
their favorite pastime such as cooking, dancing or bird-watching.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Thailand this year will continue to promote
domestic tourism and encourage Thais to tour their own country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
