<HEADLINE> Major Rebel Base Destroyed in Eastern Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan government troops
destroyed a large Tamil rebel camp in Eastern province and killed
14 rebels there on Wednesday evening in a new military operation,
according to military sources here today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the troops have so far killed 21 rebels
in the offensive launched on 31 December last year and seized a
large stock of ammunition, food and equipment.
</P>
<P>
According to a rebel radio transmission intercepted by the
military, another 15 rebels were missing apart from the 14 killed,
the sources said, adding that the government side has suffered no
casualties so far.
</P>
<P>
The new offensive aims to destroy jungle strongholds of the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) in East province. The
government troops are backed by artillery and air cover and have
advanced some 12 kilometers into the jungle, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting in the past 13 years for an
independent homeland of minority Tamils in the north and east of
the Indian Ocean island country. Over 55,000 people have been
reportedly killed in the war.  
</P>
</TEXT>
