<HEADLINE> Japan Rescues Russian Sailors From Listing Tanker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese today rescued 31 of
32 crew members of a listing Russian-registered oil tanker, the
Kyodo news service quoted Maritime Safety Agency officials as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The 13,157-ton Nakhodka was abandoned when it leaked oil some
106 kilometers northeast of the Oki Islands in Shimane Prefecture,
western Japan, which is about 700 kilometers west of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
The agency sent six vessels and helicopters to rescue the
sailors after it received report on the accident, which said the
ship was listing by about 20 degrees to the left, at about 2:50
a.m (5:50 p.m. GMT Wednesday).
</P>
<P>
The sailors were found drifting in life boats in the area of
the accident at 9:35 a.m. (0:35 a.m. GMT), the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The officials indicated that waves were as high as six meters
and visibility was poor due to fog in the accident area, and the
tanker, on a voyage from China to Russia, had not been sighted.
</P>
</TEXT>
