<DOCNO> XIE19970102.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Singaporeans Go to Critical Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 2 (Xinhua) -- A total of 765,332
Singaporeans are going to the polls today to decide 36 of the 83
seats in the next session of the parliament after the ruling
People's Action Party (PAP) won the other 47 seats on the
nomination day on December 23 last year.
</P>
<P>
By mid-day, 399,278 voters, or 52.17 percent of the voting
total, cast their ballots in all the contested electoral
divisions. At stake in today's polling are six Group
Representation Constituencies (GRCs) and nine single member wards.
</P>
<P>
There are altogether 15 GRCs and nine single member
constituencies for this general election.
</P>
<P>
Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew and Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong
and 45 other PAP candidates won their seats in the parliament on
the nomination day as the opposition camp failed to field their
candidates to contest in nine of the 15 GRCs, thus returning the
PAP to power with a majority of 47 seats in the 83-member
parliament.
</P>
<P>
A total of 192 polling stations opened at 8 a.m. local time
(0000GMT) today in the contested constituencies and will close at
8 p.m. (1200GMT), giving voters 12 hours to cast their ballots.
</P>
<P>
As early as 7 a.m. this morning (2300GMT Wednesday), queues
were seen outside a number of polling stations.
</P>
<P>
Many voters said they wanted to finish voting early so that
they could either start their daily business or go back home to
enjoy one more day off after the New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
The government has declared the polling day as a public
holiday.
</P>
<P>
Voters streamed in quietly and orderly at a polling station
near Jalan Bahagia in the central part of the island country, a
constituency where election battles raged on between the PAP and
the Singapore Democratic Party (SDP).
</P>
<P>
The Cheng San GRCs, being contested between the PAP and the
opposition Workers' Party, is the hottest spot in this general
election, which had not been expected before the election
campaigns started late last month.
</P>
<P>
"So by a strange turn of events, Cheng San becomes the focus of
this whole election. The prime minister, two deputy prime
ministers, are coming down ... to show the importance of Cheng
San. If they lose ... this government is diminished. And because
they are diminished, you will also realize, there are grave
consequences for Singapore all round, including Cheng San," Lee
Kuan Yew said at a PAP mass rally on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Workers' Party somehow became the most
formidable rival for the PAP candidates in Cheng San. The party
drew big crowds, sometimes tens of thousands, to its mass rallies,
at which its candidates challenged the policies and programs of
the ruling PAP.
</P>
<P>
Goh Chok Tong said last night that the PAP placed all its
election chips on the table of Cheng San GRC. If the party wins
today, residents in the ward will benefit from a
"winner-takes-all" package of the PAP's programs which will
include estate upgrading and extended subway service, he said.
</P>
<P>
But if Cheng San GRC voters opt for the opposition Workers'
Party, very serious consequences would be brought to Singapore and
internationally, he warned.
</P>
<P>
Goh said that he and two deputy prime ministers have staked
their prestige against the Workers' Party and its candidates,
stressing that this is the way the PAP is fighting today's
election.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970102.0112 </DOCNO>
