<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crime Fighting Atop Philippines' Agenda for 1997, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
said here today that his government would put the fight against
crime as one of its top priorities for 1997.
</P>
<P>
Delivering an Address to the Nation in the Presidential Palace,
he said the country is now being challenged by the threat posed by
crime, which must be cracked down not by conciliation but by
competent law enforcement and administration.
</P>
<P>
"Civil society has been lacerated by crime these past years. If
there is one area in which the word 'war' is appropriate, it is in
our fight against crime," he said.
</P>
<P>
During the past year, crime rate in the country has reportedly
not fallen despite the efforts of the government. 147 cases of
kidnapping were reported with 241 hostages involved. At least ten
of them were killed after their families failed to pay the ransoms
demanded.
</P>
<P>
Rape, murder and robbery cases have also increased in the past
12 months. To curb the increasing crime, the government has
resumed death penalty and will inject the first convict to death
in March this year.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Ramos also revealed other priorities his
government would undertake in the year, including the pursuit of
peace talks with other rebel groups, the development of national
economy, the measures taken to alleviate mass poverty and the
strengthening of relationship with other nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
