<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Site of Primitive Human Found in Shennongjia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, January 2 (Xinhua) -- A cave believed to be the home, or
at least a resting place, of a group of people living between
10,000 and 100,000 years ago has been discovered in Shennongjia
Valley in central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists said that they have unearthed some 30 pieces of
stone tools used by human beings in the Stone Age, together with a
large number of fossils belonging to mammals that have become
extinct both in China and throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Among the tools are sharp utensils such as scrapers and
hatchets, mainly made of black flint. They are unlike the stone
tools that have already been excavated in other regions of central
China.
</P>
<P>
The 100-meter-deep limestone cave is located at Hongpingyanbao
in Shennongjia, some 2,100 meters above the sea level.
</P>
<P>
Shennongjia Valley is a natural reserve area, famous for the
legendary "Wild Man" -- the Chinese version of "Big Foot" -- who
is believed to be the offspring of the giant ape, or perhaps a
creature that is half-ape, half-man.
</P>
<P>
On several occasions, Chinese scientists have sent teams to
study the phenomenon, and have found footprints that were believed
to be left by the "Wild Man."
</P>
<P>
The cave was first discovered by a farmer who was chasing a
wild cat that had stolen his hen. The man did not catch the
animal, but he did find some giant teeth in the area.
</P>
<P>
The site was excavated between November and December of 1996 by
a team led by the Hubei Relics and Archeology Institute.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists also have unearthed fossils of more than 20 types
of animals, including the primitive rhinoceros, the eastern
stegodon, giant pandas and hyenas.
</P>
<P>
Professor Wang Shancai, who is leading the team, said that
archeologists have never found so many rhinoceroses and eastern
stegodons buried in the same place in any other part of China.
</P>
<P>
The fossils belong to at least 30 primitive rhinoceroses and 10
eastern stegodons, he noted, adding that they might have been
sources of food for the primitive people.
</P>
<P>
The findings are important to the study of ancient animals as
well as the research on the lives of primitive man, according to
Wang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970102.0127 </DOCNO>
