<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bhutanese Refugees Stage Sit-In at Nepal-India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Bhutanese
refugees staged a sit-in protest at a Nepal-India border bridge
Sunday, blocking transport and causing inconvenience to people in
the border area in eastern Nepal, reports reaching here said
today.
</P>
<P>
The refugees are protesting against the forced deportation of
some 850 Bhutanese refugees from two camps in the Indian state of
West Bengal to Nepal by Indian police on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
They are holding 13 Indian buses, used to take the deported
refugees into the Nepali territory, and said that they would
return the buses only after India agrees to transport the
deportees back to India.
</P>
<P>
Traffic movement on the Mechi bridge at Nepal's eastern border
with India has been paralyzed and Nepali residents are facing a
shortage of daily consumer goods due to the blockade, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 Bhutanese refugees, mostly of Nepali origin, have
been living in several refugee camps in Nepal and India since they
were forced to flee Bhutan six years ago due to the Bhutanese
authorities' "one nation, one people" policy.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Appeal Movement Coordination Council (AMCC), a
Bhutanese refugee group, launched a series of peace marches,
trying to walk from east Nepal, via India, to Thimphu, the capital
of Bhutan, to appeal for free repatriation of all Bhutanese
refugees.
</P>
<P>
However, no marchers managed to reach Thimphu as they were
either intercepted by Indian police when crossing India or evicted
by Bhutanese security troops as soon as they entered Bhutan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
