<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thriving Coastal Areas "Cradle" for Industrial Labor Force (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Twelve years ago, Li Ji was a
farmer toiling in Xuanhan County in southwest China's Sichuan
Province.
</P>
<P>
Today, he is a wealthy entrepreneur and the owner of a clothing
factory in his hometown that has turned out one million yuan
worth-of clothing since it opened in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The former farmer attributed the changes in his life to his
experience in south China's coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
In 1984, Li left his hometown to try his luck in the cities of
Guangzhou and Shenzhen in Guangdong Province. In these prosperous
areas, Li not only made a considerable profit, but also learned
garment making techniques and gleaned managerial expertise. In
1995, he returned to his hometown with 600,000 yuan and started
his own business.
</P>
<P>
Li Ji is only one of millions of farmers in central and west
China who have worked or are working in economically developed
coastal areas. Several million of them have left farming and
become industrial workers. Like Li, some have become
entrepreneurs, who now have the power to create more opportunities
for their fellow farmers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970102.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thriving Coastal Areas "Cradle" for Industrial Labor Force (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Statistics show that Sichuan, the most populous province in
China, steadily exports a labor force of more than five million to
other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Densely populated Hunan, Hubei, Henan and Jiangxi provinces
also consider the export of labor as an important measure to
stimulate their rural economies. More than one million farmers
annually migrate from each of these provinces to more economically
developed areas.
</P>
<P>
All of these changes have taken place since the 1980s, when
coastal areas were the first to take off after the country
initiated market economic reform.
</P>
<P>
As a result, a great demand for labor was created in these
rapidly developing areas. Nearly seven million rural workers have
found jobs in Guangdong's Pear River Delta alone, one of the most
prosperous areas in China. Eighty percent of them are from the
countryside and mainly engaged in construction, transportation,
repair and other processing industries.
</P>
<P>
To combat the poor quality of the rural labor force, coastal
areas provide a wide range of job training services to improve
workers' competitiveness in the job market.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1994, nearly 150 job training centers had been
set up at or above the county level in Guangdong Province, which
can train 200,000 people annually. There are also 3,600
non-government-run job services in the province, which can train
more than 500,000 people each year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970102.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thriving Coastal Areas "Cradle" for Industrial Labor Force (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A job service network has taken shape in the province, one of
China's most economically thriving areas.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the industrial structure of Shenzhen, where
there are more than two million laborers from other parts of the
country, is switching from a labor-intensive mode to one that
emphasizes good education and expertise.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities presently conduct mandatory job training for
the laborers. Nearly 10,000 employees head for various types of
job training centers after work.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, some central and western regions have put
forward new requirements for the migrating population of farmers.
</P>
<P>
Yuanba District of Guangyuan City, Sichuan Province, requires
farmers who are seeking jobs in the coastal areas to learn at
least two applied techniques. Farmers moving out of the district
now work mainly in construction, machine building, electronics,
and repair and processing trades.
</P>
<P>
The labor force flow between eastern coastal areas and central
and western regions has resulted in a new body of industrial
workers, according to analysts here.
</P>
<P>
The farmers-turned-workers are playing a significant role in
the improvement of the quality of Chinese labor force as well as
the economic development of central and western China, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
