<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Hakim Ali Zardari, former
member of Pakistan's National Assembly and father-in-law of
deposed prime minister Benazir Bhutto, was arrested today on
charges of embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Investigating Agency (FIA) raided Zardari's
residence in Karachi early this morning after receiving orders
from Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
The authorities did not disclose the detailed reasons for
Zardari's arrest.
</P>
<P>
Aslam Hayat Qureshi, former chief secretary of Punjab province,
was also arrested at his residence in Lahore.
</P>
<P>
FIA sources revealed that Qureshi was arrested on charges of
amassing wealth by misusing his official powers under the Benazir
Bhutto administration.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believed that the arrests of Hakim Zardari and
Aslam Qureshi were connected with the corruption case of Asif
Zardari, Benazir Bhutto's husband who has been under police
custody since Benazir stepped down in November last year.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Ministry has charged Qureshi with accepting Asif
Zardari's illegal orders through which he deprived the national
exchequer of millions of rupees (one U.S. dollar equals 40
rupees).
</P>
<P>
Since President Farooq Leghari dissolved Benazir's government
on November 5, 1996, the caretaker government has been staging an
accountability movement in the country.
</P>
<P>
The FIA sources said that more politicians would be arrested in
the next few days on corruption charges.  
</P>
