<HEADLINE> Successful Aid-the-Poor Effort in China's Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, January 2 (Xinhua) -- A total of 562,000 rural
residents in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region have
gotten out of poverty this year by using science and technology.
</P>
<P>
A technological project to grow crops on dry land by using
plastic sheets helped mountainous and arid areas in inner Mongolia
to harvest 1.3 billion kg of grain in 1996, 500 million kg more
than in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Local farmers report a substantial increase in income from
production of grain, vegetables, and melons, thanks to the use of
the technolgy.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1.5 million people have benefited from the region's
aid-the-poor projects over the past eight years, but desert areas
in inner Mongolia cover more than 30 million hectares, and there
are nearly three million people who still have not solved the food
problem.
</P>
<P>
The region's agriculture, financial, and civil affairs
departments say they will use team work to help another 700,000
persons get out of poverty next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
