<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tianjin Supervises Medicines With Adverse Reactions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The city of Tianjin has
established a center to supervise the harmful reactions of
medicines.
</P>
<P>
The center will test the safety of a variety of medicines,
collect information on medicines suspected of having adverse
reactions, provide dosage indexes and offer a public information
service.
</P>
<P>
China has established seven such facilities and 85 supervisory
hospitals in 26 provinces and municipalities.
</P>
<P>
Adverse reactions include any physical responses that occur
when approved medicine is taken according to directions, and in
the proper dosage.
</P>
<P>
Side effects, and toxic, allergic and delayed reactions to
medicine also will be studied.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Health Organization, five percent of
China's more than 50 million annual in-patients are hospitalized
as a result of negative reactions to medicine. The number of
people suffering from serious side effects exceeds 250,000.
</P>
<P>
Peng Dunren, a member of the expert committee of the center,
said that although the approval for the production of new
medicines is strict in China, adverse reactions still occur
because of limited clinical trial use.
</P>
<P>
About three fourths of the harmful reactions can be prevented,
Peng believed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
