<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Quick Response System for Quake Disaster Relief Operational </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, January 2 (Xinhua) -- China's first quick
response system that predicts earthquakes and provides aftershock
disaster relief is now in operation in the city of Qinhuangdao.
</P>
<P>
Feng Suming, an expert with the city's seismological bureau,
said the system is able to make more timely and precise quake
predictions, and can rapidly arrange pre-quake preparations and
post-quake relief.
</P>
<P>
He added that after a strong earthquake, the system can
automatically report the time, place and degree of the quake,
scale of the disaster, the areas hit with major shocks, and
disaster relief plans.
</P>
<P>
Covering an area of 5,400 square kilometers in north China's
Hebei Province, the system consists of several remote sensing
stations, a quake information data bank, radio tracking systems
and mobile communication networks.
</P>
<P>
The computerized center is connected with the State
Seismological Bureau, the mayor's office and the city's quake
prediction and disaster relief radio tracking station.
</P>
<P>
Feng said with the help of the system, the city government
could better issue quake information to the public and carry out
its emergency relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
Feng said if an especially strong quake rendered the city
unable to implement its disaster-relief arrangements, the system
is designed to request help from the provincial government or the
central government.
</P>
<P>
Qinhuangdao is a well-known tourist spot in China, and one of
Asia's biggest ports for transporting energy products.
</P>
<P>
In 1976, a devastating earthquake struck the city of Tangshan,
which is near Qinhuangdao. Now, Qinhuangdao, Beijing and most of
the areas in north China are the country's major earthquake-prone
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970102.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Pledges to Improve Quality of State Assets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The years that remain in the
20th century will be an important period in China's drive to
improve the quality of its state-owned assets, a senior official
said.
</P>
<P>
"To optimize our economic growth mode and meet the challenges
posed by competition in overall national strength, we should
energetically develop the state-owned economy, and significantly
improve the quality of our state assets," said Vice-Minister of
Finance Zhang Youcai.
</P>
<P>
"We must make a new breakthrough in our work of administering
state-owned assets," said Zhang, who is also director of the State
Administration of State Assets.
</P>
<P>
The management of state assets during the Ninth Five-Year Plan
period (1996-2000) should be improved to the level of "bringing
into full play the position of the public economy and the leading
role of the state-owned economy," he noted.
</P>
<P>
To that end, China should make several changes in the
administration of state property, such as making it more
market-oriented, focusing more on restructuring the state economy
as a whole rather than on single enterprises and placing equal
emphasis on operational and non-operational assets, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that China's state assets had exceeded
5.72 trillion yuan (about 688 billion US dollars) in value by the
end of 1995. The yearly increase of the asset value has been
accelerating, from 12.4 percent since 1949 to 14.5 percent since
1980, and 17.9 percent since 1990.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
