<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Officials to Study in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- As part of its preparations to
develop closer economic ties with southeast Asian countries, China
will send a group of ten officials to study at Mekong College in
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The college will help train senior management personnel for
countries within the Lancang-Mekong River Sub-Regional Economic
Zone, including Thailand, Laos, Burma, Vietnam, Kampuchea and
China.
</P>
<P>
The selection process, conducted by a coordination office for
the project in Yunnan Province, required each candidate to pass
strict qualification examinations and English proficiency tests.
</P>
<P>
Mekong College, formally known as the Great Mekong River
Sub-Regional Economic Development and Cooperation College, was
established by the governments of New Zealand and Thailand in
November 1994.
</P>
<P>
Economic cooperations between these countries have been largely
promoted over these years, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand government invested 12.59 million New Zealand
dollars in the training program. The Thai government plans to
funnel five million Thai Baht annually from 1996 to 2001, while
the country's Khon Kaen University will provide facilities and pay
the salaries of part-time lecturers.
</P>
<P>
The college plans to arrange three courses every year,
beginning with the first training class that starts in February.
</P>
</TEXT>
