<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Plans to Reopen Embassy in Kabul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is planning to reopen
its embassy in the Afghan capital of Kabul, the local newspaper
"The News" reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted official sources as saying, "The embassy in
Kabul is almost open as some of the staff have already been there
and are operating from a house."
</P>
<P>
Three houses are being acquired to accommodate the Pakistani
mission in Kabul in the near future, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that Aziz Khan, Pakistan's ambassador to
Malaysia, has been appointed as the new Pakistani ambassador to
Afghanistan and he is scheduled to pay a farewell call on the
Malaysian king on January 6 before flying home.
</P>
<P>
Then he will visit Kabul some time in mid-January to see the
situation there and plan the formal reopening of the embassy.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's embassy in Kabul was attacked on September 6, 1995,
by thousands of protesters reportedly sent by the then government
led by President Burhanuddin Rabbani for alleged Pakistani support
for the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
However, both the then Pakistani and Afghan governments denied
the allegations.
</P>
<P>
During the attack, an employee of the embassy was killed and
Ambassador Qazi Humayun and military attache Ashraf Afridi were
wounded.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan later evacuated its embassy staff and closed the
embassy. However, the Pakistani consulates in the Afghan cities of
Jalalabad, Kandahar, Herat and Mazar-i-Sharif continued to
operate.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believed that Pakistan would become the first
country to have a diplomatic presence in the Taliban-controlled
Kabul if its embassy started functioning in the Afghan capital.
</P>
<P>
Since the Taliban captured Kabul on September 27, 1996, no
country has formally recognized the Taliban regime in the Afghan
capital.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
