<HEADLINE> China Opens First Wholesale Market for Electronic Publications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- China has set up its first
wholesale market for electronic publications and computer software
to help combat copyright infringement, the "China Youth News"
reported.
</P>
<P>
The market is located in northwest Beijing's Zhongguancun
district, known as China's "Silicon Valley," which is densely
populated with computer stores.
</P>
<P>
The market is the first of its kind engaged in the wholesale of
authorized electronic publications and software under the guidance
of government departments.
</P>
<P>
The article added that the market should help to regulate the
sector, fight against copyright piracy, and protect intellectual
property rights.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 900 overseas-invested companies and about
20,000 Chinese firms engaged in developing and selling computer
software in Beijing, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Previous reports said that the country confiscated more than 10
million illegal and unauthorized LDs, CD and other publications in
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
