<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest China's First Urban River Regulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, January 2 (Xinhua) -- China's first local regulation
for controlling urban rivers has been promulgated by the
government of Chengdu, the captial of Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
The Regulation of Chengdu City on Comprehensive Treatment,
Development, and Management of the Fuhe and Nanhe rivers will
provide a model for other Chinese cities for curbing water
pollution, protecting the urban environment, and promoting urban
construction, experts say.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulation, a special committee will be set up
to organize the work, and any large project involving the rivers
is subject to approval by the committee, and any profit from
development of the rivers is to be used for further treatment.
</P>
<P>
The Fuhe and Nanhe are the major rivers that flow through urban
parts of Chengdu. A comprehensive project to harness the Nanhe
river was started in 1992.  
</P>
</TEXT>
