<HEADLINE> China Allows More Programs to Be Relayed by Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has given
the green light to a Guangxi TV station and radio station to
broadcast programs to foreign countries via satellite this year.
</P>
<P>
The People's Radio Station and the TV Station of the Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region will rent the Asiasat-2 to air their
shows, which will reach more than 30 countries and regions in
south and southeast Asia as well as Australia.
</P>
<P>
The coastal autonomous region in southwest China shares a
lengthy borderline with Vietnam, and serves as a gateway for China
to do business with southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The programs will be broadcast daily for a total of 18 hours,
local officials said.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, more than ten provincial-level TV stations
have launched satellite broadcasts with the approval of the
Beijing-based Ministry of Radio, Film and Television.
</P>
<P>
China's most comprehensive satellite programs for overseas
audiences are aired by the state-run Central Television
Station. 
</P>
