<HEADLINE> Standardization Atop Agenda for Listed Firms, Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Listed companies in China should
give priority to standardizing their operations, as this will
benefit both the development of the firms and the country's
fledgling stock market.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Daojiong, Chairman of the China Securities Regulatory
Commission, made the remarks at a two-day seminar on the
standardization of firms listed in 1996. The seminar was held in
Dongguan, Guangdong Province, from December 27-28.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of 180 new listed firms participated in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, the official noted that the growth of the stock
market should serve the economic reform and the sustained, speedy
and healthy development of the national economy. He called on
these listed companies to welcome the current enterprise reform.
</P>
<P>
The listed companies must work diligently to improve their
communication networks, to abide by the legal-person system, to
utilize their funds strictly in line with their share-issuing
documents, to stop trading their own shares, and to reinforce
supervision of decision-making and risk management in high-risk
industries, according to Zhou.
</P>
<P>
He urged authorities of various sectors to support listed
enterprises and to create a sound environment for these firms.
</P>
</TEXT>
