<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Doubles Fuel Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Romania started to double fuel
oil prices today, in a bid to make them more comparable with those
in the international market.
</P>
<P>
The price for gasoline jumped to 1900 leus (40 U.S. cents) per
liter from 900 leus per liter, and for diesel oil, up to 1300 leus
(26 cents) per liter from 680 leus per liter.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian government decided to raise the prices at the end
of last year, after leu depreciated against the U.S. dollar. By
the end of 1996, gasoline price dropped to five liters per dollar
and drivers in neighboring countries flock in to fill their gas
tanks, taking advantage of leu's depreciation.
</P>
<P>
Romanian Prime Minister Victor Ciorbea said the nation's oil
refineries would suffer more losses if current prices remained
unchanged. He said Romanian refineries had lost 880 billion leus
(170 million dollars) because of leu's depreciation.
</P>
<P>
The price hike for fuel oil also led to price increases for
food and train fare.
</P>
<P>
Ciorbea said the government will increase social welfare and
take other compensational measures to counteract the negative
consequences caused to consumers by the price hikes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
