<DOCNO> XIE19970102.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Level Rises in Bangladeshi River Under Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- A slight rise in water level has
been witnessed in Bangladesh's Padma River as the quantum of water
stipulated in the Ganges water-sharing treaty with India was
released from India's Farakka Barrage Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The prime ministers of the two neighboring countries signed the
30- year treaty on December 12 last year, which took effect on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Hydrology Department of the Bangladesh Water
Department Board, the water level of the river increased by seven
centimeters at the Rajshahi point in the northwest and 57
centimeters at the Hardinge Bridge point bordering India Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
For the whole day, Bangladesh received 79,041 cusecs of water
of the Ganges, sources concerned confirmed.
</P>
<P>
According to the water treaty, Bangladesh will get a maximum of
67,516 cusecs of water between January 1-10 and a minimum of
27,633 cusecs during April 11-20 in the lean period.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's northern and northwestern regions had been subject
to severe water crisis in the dry months from January to May
because of alleged "unilateral withdrawal" of the water of the
common Ganges River by India at the Farakka Barrage in the absence
of any agreement whatsoever since 1988.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people gathered on both banks of the Padma River
in different parts of the northwestern district of Rajshahi to
watch the flow of the Ganges water. But the curious people were
not satisfied as the Padma flow was not heavy.
</P>
<P>
It would take two to three days for the augmented Ganges flow
to roll down the water-scanty district, an expert explained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
