<DOCNO> XIE19970102.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laos, U.S. Seeking Better Trade Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Laos and the United States are
expected to reopen negotiations early this year on conclusion of a
trade agreement which will allow Laos to win US trade privileges
with its improvement of investment environment, a local newspaper
said here today.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations are expected to begin in the areas of
investment and intellectual property rights, US embassy sources in
Vientiane were quoted as saying by "the Nation".
</P>
<P>
Human rights and labor standards and legal system will be the
next targeted issues for the negotiations, they said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will be modeled after the one that the United
States reached with Cambodia in October last year, in which the US
granted most-favored-nation (MFN) status to Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted the sources as saying that Washington set
no preconditions for granting Laos MFN status, but the Lao economy
must become genuinely market-driven on the basis of competition
instead of monopoly.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations on MFN status for Laos, which started in
Vientiane in October last year, are expected to clear the last
hurdle in the full normalization of bilateral ties since the two
countries agreed to upgrade their relations in 1993, according to
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The United States earlier last year agreed to lift the
two-decade-old embargo on economic assistance to Laos in exchange
of Laos' cooperation in narcotics suppression and efforts to
excavate the bones of American servicemen missing in Laos during
the Indochina wars.
</P>
<P>
In June this year, the two countries reached an agreement to
assist Laos in demining and retrieving unexplored ordnance.
</P>
<P>
Lao Foreign Minister Somsavat Lengsavad has said that Laos
hopes to conclude the MFN deal with the U.S. before it joined the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) next July.
</P>
<P>
Washington reportedly was satisfied with Lao's preparations for
joining the global market reform and the two countries are
studying a proposed draft agreement on trade.
</P>
<P>
The United States currently is the second largest investor in
Laos after Thailand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
