<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourism in Cuba Booms in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The tourism industry in Cuba saw
an unprecedented boom in 1996 as more than one million foreigners
visited the country, a 30 percent increase compared to the year
before.
</P>
<P>
Gross revenues of the industry reached 1.3 billion U.S. dollars
in 1996, making it one of the largest sources of hard currency for
this Caribbean island, according to official preliminary
statistics.
</P>
<P>
With its enviable weather and idyllic beaches, Cuba has
attracted a great number of tourists mostly from Europe and the
American continent.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Organization of Tourism (WOT), Cuba has
become the second most favorite tourist destination for Italians
and the third for Spaniards. It is also the fourth tourist
destination chosen by Canadians, Mexicans and Germans, the sixth
for the French, the seventh for Argentines and the 10th for
Brazilians.
</P>
<P>
Despite the Helms-Burton Act promulgated on March 12 by the
United States Government to frighten foreign investors away from
the island, Cuba has 36 contracts signed with oversea companies on
hotel administration and joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
Even before 1989, when economic reform began, tourism had
become the only sector in which foreign capital was allowed to
enter and joint ventures to emerge.
</P>
<P>
And when Cuba's worst economic crisis, since the triumph of the
1959 revolution, broke out in 1989, the tourism industry proved of
great help in offsetting the depression with the fresh money and
hard currency it generated.
</P>
<P>
This open-door policy also enriched the Cubans first-hand
knowledge about the industry which had been a novelty to them.
</P>
<P>
Advanced ways of management and marketing were adopted by many
hotels, which also presented an example for other sectors of the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
Tourism soon would be capable of competing with the sugar
industry, the country's traditional pillar industry.
</P>
<P>
With the glorious past at sight, Cuba is confident of
maintaining a promising future for tourism in the new year.
</P>
<P>
The Tourism Ministry's studies shows Cuba has the capacity for
150,000 to 155,000 hotel rooms by the year 2000. There were 27,000
rooms available for international tourists at the end of 1996,
when some 4,200 hotel rooms were finished or re-decorated.
</P>
<P>
With the coming of the December to March busy season, the
country hopes to receive about 450,000 foreign holiday makers.
</P>
<P>
Ministry authorities estimated that tourism would guarantee
Cuba more than 1.2 million visitors in 1997, and two million in
2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
