<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup:  China Becoming Active Force in Multilateral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China, as a permanent member of the UN Security Council, has
always opposed hegemonism and power politics, and maintained the
interests of developing countries by adhering to principles and
upholding justice in the affairs of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
For instance, China plays a special role in promoting the UN's
fair and balanced approach to various problems by supporting the
organization's efforts in handling global political disagreements
and regional conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The country stresses that the work of the international
community, including UN peace-keeping actions, should strictly
abide by the standards of respecting national sovereignty,
non-interference in internal affairs and peacefully solving
disputes.
</P>
<P>
China holds it is a violation of the UN Charter and a threat to
world peace and stability to interfere in other countries'
internal affairs for various excuses, or to be prone to imposing
sanctions, or to use violence.
</P>
<P>
In the election of the UN secretary-general, which was just
finalized, China firmly backed the position of the Organization of
African Unity, winning the gratitude of developing countries,
especially the African nations.
</P>
<P>
As for the human rights issue, China advocates international
cooperation on the basis of equality and mutual respect, but is
against interference in any country's internal affairs in the name
of human rights.
</P>
<P>
For the sixth time, China successfully challenged, with a wide
show of support, the anti-China motion submitted by some Western
countries at the 52nd session of the UN Human Rights Commission in
April, and maintained its national sovereignty and dignity.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, China enhanced its mutual understanding on
the issue with the parties concerned through active bilateral
exchanges and discussions on the basis of equality and mutual
respect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970102.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup:  China Becoming Active Force in Multilateral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China worked vigorously to achieve complete disarmament by
taking numerous actions to attain the goal.
</P>
<P>
The country made a great contribution to the conclusion of the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty through active participation and a
flexible approach during the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
China also was involved in extensive multilateral projects that
positively affected the economy and society, and put forward a
series of constructive proposals to bring about much-needed
changes in these fields.
</P>
<P>
It urged developed nations to take effective measures to create
a more favorable external environment for the economic growth of
the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
It holds that the developed countries should offer those that
are developing new and additional funding and technology on
preferential terms, in order to enhance sustained development of
the growing nations.
</P>
<P>
China stresses that international cooperation in social growth
should be conducted on the basis of equality and mutual benefit,
and should respect each country's right to choose its own
political system and economic mode. Prerequisites to cooperation
should be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
China's worldwide involvement in social advancement has greatly
enhanced the healthy development of international cooperation in
this area.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, China has made great strides in its pursuit
of an independent foreign policy of peace, and also in its
participation in bilateral diplomacy, said Zhang Yishan, deputy
director of the the Department of International Organizations and
Conferences of China's Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
He said China will continue to carry out the independent
foreign policy of peace, and participate in multilateral efforts
in the fields of politics, economy, disarmament and social
development.
</P>
<P>
It will live up to its status as a permanent member of the UN
Security Council, oppose hegemonism and power politics, and work
diligently to safeguard the interests of developing nations, Zhang
said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated China is determined to make efforts with other
countries to establish a new international political and economic
order that is peaceful, fair and reasonable.  
</P>
</TEXT>
