<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Property Rights Transfer Helps Ailing Enterprises (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- In the three years since China
introduced the system of property rights transfer to bail out its
debt-ridden state-owned firms, more than 1,000 of the businesses
have been merged in Shandong and Zhejiang provinces, and some
1,200 have been sold each year in Zhejiang, Shanxi and Ningxia.
</P>
<P>
At present, more than 200 property rights transfer agencies are
flourishing in China as a result of the nationwide reform of
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The agencies, which were established to advance the modern
enterprise system launched by China in 1993, handle the combining,
merging, acquisition and share-holding, and restructuring of
state-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the system is to clarify property rights, individual
rights and responsibilities, separate government functions from
those of the enterprises and introduce scientific management.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the readjustment of property rights in state firms
worked well in most parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
As the reform swept across China, the central government pushed
ahead with the re-organization of state-owned enterprises and
supervised the smooth flow of inventory assets. The experiment to
optimize capital structure extended from 18 Chinese cities to 50,
and the total assets involved jumped from 148 billion yuan to 183
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the debt of state-owned enterprises has been
reduced by 7.1 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
Hainan Toothpaste Plant, formerly one of the leading companies
of its kind, was in the red due to lack of funds and poor
management. In 1994, the plant ownership was transferred to an
industrial and trading company, and the new business underwent
technological renovation and initiated a new marketing system,
pushing its output value to 100 million yuan. Of this amount, 70
million yuan was profit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970102.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Property Rights Transfer Helps Ailing Enterprises (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Despite the many success stories, experts say China's property
rights trading volume is still small. Negative attitudes, poor
communications, lack of talented personnel, restrictions, laws and
transaction supervision agencies have also hindered the
development of the trading.
</P>
<P>
To create a smoother flow of information, the State
Administration of State Property set up a national property rights
transaction information network last July. The transaction
information will soon be available on the Internet, government
sources said.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang Youcai, director of the State Administration
of State Property, to reduce the loss of state property -- a key
issue in property rights transfers and trading -- the government
will establish a system to register property and supervise
property appraisal. Laws and regulations regarding property rights
reform are being worked out, he said.
</P>
<P>
Property rights transactions can help attract more overseas
capital, and promote the readjustment of the industrial setup so
that the state-owned enterprises can improve their economic
performance, said Wang Tong, director of an information center
affiliated with the State Commission for Restructuring the Economy.
</P>
<P>
Other experts have suggested that China should establish a
nationwide, open and competitive property rights trading market so
that such deals can play a more important role in the reform of
state-owned enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
