<HEADLINE> IRA Launches The New Year with A Bomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 1 (Xinhua) -- British army bomb experts have
carried out a controlled explosion on a van left in the grounds of
Belfast castle which the Irish Republican Army (IRA) said
contained a land-mine.
</P>
<P>
The IRA said security checks had forced it to abandon the
vehicle last night. Security has been stepped up across Northern
Ireland and in mainland Britain since the IRA abandoned a
cease-fire last February in a 27-year campaign to end British rule.
</P>
<P>
Tension increased recently with signs that pro-British Loyalist
guerrillas might end a two-year truce. Booby trap bombs were
placed under cars belonging to senior republicans, injuring one of
them.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland Secretary Patrick Mayhew said today the IRA's
message for the New Year was that they had not turned away from
violence. And he branded the IRA "criminal gangsters".
</P>
<P>
David Trimble, Ulster Unionist party leader, told the Today
Program that it was consistent with IRA activity over the last
couple of months.
</P>
<P>
"There's no indication whatsoever that the IRA are
contemplating politics. Every indication is that they are trying
to step up activity," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It's time all the other parties in the inter-party talks took
this on board," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
