<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polling Starts in Singapore General Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Polling started here today in
the eighth General Election of Singapore, with 36 out of a total
of 83 Parliament seats at stake.
</P>
<P>
The other 47 seats were already won by the ruling People's
Action Party (PAP) on the Nomination Day on December 23, last
year, when the opposition camp failed to field enough candidates
to contest in nine of the 24 constituencies.
</P>
<P>
The PAP fielded a total of 83 candidates, while the five
opposition parties came up with only 38 candidates to run in the
race. In addition, there was one independent candidate, thus
making it a total of 39 from the opposition camp.
</P>
<P>
This time, there are 1,881,011 eligible voters in Singapore, an
island country with a population of almost three million. The
voters are divided into 24 constituencies, namely, 15 Group
Representation Constituencies (GRCs) and nine single-seat
constituencies.
</P>
<P>
Since 47 PAP candidates already won walkovers in nine GRCs on
the Nomination Day, real election battles are only being fought in
the rest of the six GRCs and nine single-seat constituencies.
Final results of the contests will come out late tonight or early
Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
A total of 765,332 voters from the 15 contesting
constituencies, or about 40.69 percent of the nation's entire
eligible voters, will cast their ballots at 192 polling stations
to decide the remaining 36 seats, despite the fact that the PAP
was already returned to power ten days ago.
</P>
<P>
Counting of the votes will be decentralized for the first time
this time as the number of counting centers were increased to 42
from eight in the last general election in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The first result could be in as early as 10:30 p.m. tonight and
it was expected that everything could be completed by midnight,
about two hours earlier than in the past, Returning Officer Tan
Boon Huat said last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the first winner should be declared at about 10:30
p.m. or 11 p.m. on the polling day, about an hour earlier than
usual. In the past elections, results streamed in till about 2
a.m. the next day.
</P>
<P>
When voting closes at 8 p.m. this evening, the ballot boxes
will be sealed and taken to the counting centers. Each counting
center has a number of counting places, each of which is, on
average, in charge of the ballot papers of one polling station.
</P>
<P>
The results of each counting place will be transmitted by fax
and modem to one of the seven announcement centers, where results
will be tallied and announced.
</P>
<P>
According to the Returning Officer, about 5,000 civil servants
and staff members of statutory boards are deployed today to help
run the election.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970102.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
