<HEADLINE> Public Information Network For Chinese Island Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Residents of south China's Hainan
Province will be able to look through newspapers in other parts of
the world or do stock trading on their computers at home in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
They will also benefit from a provincial public information
network completed at the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the provincial Economic Information Center say
that the network shows that the province has made its first step
toward getting on the information superhighway.
</P>
<P>
The network will make it possible for residents, provincial
government agencies, and businesses to contact each other
electronically, and will connect them to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Within the next few days, an international travel services
system will be operational, connecting travel agencies, hotels,
scenic spots, transportation companies, and customs offices via
the network.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, Hainan has built up its public
telecommunications, exchanges, and public security monitoring
network. 
</P>
</TEXT>
