<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Population Reaches 199.7 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia had a population of
199.7 million by the end of 1996, making it the world fourth most
populous country after China, India and the United States, a
senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"The figure is based on the projection by the National
Coordinating Board for Family Planning (BKKBN), in cooperation
with the Central Bureau of Statistics (BPS) and other relevant
agencies," State Minister for Population Haryono Suyono said.
</P>
<P>
At a seminar on policy and strategy for contraceptive services
held here Tuesday, he said the figure is lower than that predicted
previously, Antara news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
"This is the result of our hard work in reducing the country's
birth rate from six percent in 1970 to 2.6 percent in 1996," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Some experts have projected that the Indonesian population will
reach 280 million by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Haryono also said Indonesia has succeeded in reducing the
mortality rate from 145 out of every 1,000 births in 1970 to 55
out of every 1,000 births in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
