<HEADLINE> Bailey Plans to Defend Title in Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Olympic 100-meter champion
Donovan Bailey said on Tuesday he plans to defend his title at the
2000 Summer Games in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old Canadian had said previously that he didn't see
himself sticking around for another Olympic cycle, but his plans
appear to have changed.
</P>
<P>
"There's still a lot left," he said. "I still pursue the dream
of running a perfect race, or a race with the least amount of
mistakes."
</P>
<P>
Besides winning the Olympic sprint in world-record time, Bailey
teamed with Bruny Surin, Glenroy Gilbert and Robert Esmie to win
the 400-meter relay.
</P>
<P>
Bailey said his goals for 1997 include setting a world record
with his relay partners, lowering his own work mark and breaking
the Canadian record in the 200 meters. The 1997 World
Championships are scheduled for Athens, Greece, in August.
</P>
</TEXT>
