<HEADLINE> Chile to Double Anti-drug Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The government of Chile will
double its grants to the anti-drug war in 1997 to finance more
prevention programs to save more young people from addiction.
</P>
<P>
The budget allocated to the war against drugs will rise from
the equivalent of 2.7 million U.S.dollars in 1996 to 5.76 million
dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The amounts spent in fighting drugs have been increasing
steadily in Chile since 1992, from an equivalent of 12,195 dollars
that year to 134,146 in 1993, 395,000 in 1994 and 914,000 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the police seized about 730 kilograms of cocaine, more
than a ton of cocaine paste, three kilograms of coca leaves and
122 tons of marijuana of different kinds.
</P>
<P>
The police also caught 6,454 people involved in drugs, and
impounded 148 vehicles, 131 fire arms and 39 portable
phones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
