<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Builds "Cultural Corridor" Along Silk Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, January 2 (Xinhua) -- China has invested 34 million
yuan (about four million US dollars) to build a "Cultural
Corridor" along the Silk Road -- the ancient trade route that
connected central Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said the project was launched in the Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region in northwest China, where a number of
libraries, museums and bookstores have been built.
</P>
<P>
The endeavor has also promoted other cultural activities,
including dance and song performances in villages throughout the
border area.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that the project will enrich the cultural lives
of the Uygur ethnic group in the autonomous region, which is
thousands miles away from Beijing and has a unique cultural
tradition.
</P>
<P>
The region was prosperous some 1,000 years ago, when major
sections of the Silk Road passed through the area. The passage
later disappeared due to the expansion of the desert area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
