<HEADLINE> Chinese Newspaper Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
Major Beijing-based newspapers including the "People's Daily",
the Overseas Edition of the "People's Daily", "China Youth Daily",
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph" and "Beijing Daily" all frontpaged the
important speech made by President Jiang Zemin at the new year
reception given by the National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) in Beijing on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Jiang hailed the achievements ther Chinese
people have scored in the reform, opening-up and modernization
drive, and extended greetings to non-Communist parties, persons
without any party affiliation, workers, farmers, intellectuals and
cadres, officers and men of the People's Liberation Army, police
officers, and to compatriots in Taiwan, Hong Kong, Macao and
Chinese nationals residing abroad overseas, and friends all over
the world.
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- A ceremony was held in Beijing's Capital International
Airport Wednesday to welcome the first overseas tourist group to
China this year. The event also marked the inauguration of
Visit China '97, a move highlighting China's tourism business for
this year. Similar activities were also held in cities of
Shanghai, Xi'an, Hangzhou, Nanjing, Fuzhou and Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- People across China celebrated the first day of the new year
with joyful gatherings, looking for the new year to be more
promising and hopeful.
</P>
<P>
At 7:36 this morning, more than 50,000 people throughout China
came to Tian'anmen Square to watch the national flag-raising
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin, in a New Year message broadcast
worldwide on Tuesday, called on statesmen of all countries to
co-operate and work towards the goal of eliminating war and
poverty, safeguarding world peace and promoting the common
development of the global community.
</P>
<P>
-- China's steel production surpassed 100 million tons in 1996,
outpacing Japan to become the top producer in the world, the
Ministry of the Metallurgical Industry announced on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
