<HEADLINE> Uruguay Closes 1996 With 23.5 Percent Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Uruguay reported a monthly
inflation of 1.1 percent in December to close 1996 with an annual
total of 23.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics released today, the downward
trend for inflation actually began a year earlier, when price
increases dropped to an average of 25 percent in 1995 from 41
percent two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate in Uruguay last year was the lowest since the
previous low of 1981, when it recorded 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
As in 1995, the inflation of wholesale prices in 1996 was lower
than that of consumer prices, which closed at 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Prices for plant and animal products increased 29 percent in
1996, the highest gain among all sectors, due to a 33 percent hike
on the international agricultural market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
