<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long-Term Goals For East Chinese Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Qingdao Port, a major coastal
outlet in China's Shandong Province, plans to become a major moder
port in the world, with an annual handling capacity of 120 million
tons by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The port is the country's first harbor capable of handling the
world's most advanced container ships, and ranks third in China
after Shanghai and Dalian in terms of annual container handling
capacity.
</P>
<P>
This year, 800,000 containers are expected to be handled, and
at least 1.5 million containers will be handled by the year 2000,
according to the port authority.
</P>
<P>
Since 1988, the port has put three billion yuan into revamping
an old harbor area, and building a new one, and six new deep-water
berths at the new area have gone into operation, increasing the
port's annual capacity to 80 million tons.
</P>
<P>
To date, it has opened ten container shipping routes to the
United States, Japan, Japan, Hong Kong, the Persian Gulf,
southeast Asia, Europe and the Republic of Korea. Its container
handling capacity has risen at an annual average rate of 40
percent over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
According to the overall plan, about 60 berths will be built in
the new area in the next few years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
