<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Lowers Investments Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
lowered its investments target for 1997 from 21 billion to 18
billion U.S. dollars, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the government made the adjustment amid
concerns that nervous foreign investors could postpone their
investment plans this year because of political uncertainties
after 1998.
</P>
<P>
The country has recently witnessed a constitutional amendment
drive to change the term limits of President Fidel Ramos, who is
to step down in 1998 under the constitution.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ramos' health has become a sensitive issue after he
underwent an operation before Christmas to remove a block in the
artery in his neck.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, the new target will cover projects to
be registered with the four government incentive-giving bodies --
the Board of Investments, the Philippine Economic Zone Authority,
the Subic Bay Metropolitan Authority and the Clark Development
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
International observers said the Philippine government should
work hard to raise the proportion of direct investments in its
total amount of investments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
