<HEADLINE> Peru Records Two Digits Inflation In 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Peru had 11.84 percent inflation
during 1996, 1.64 percent more than the previous year, said the
National Institute of Statistics and Computer Database.
</P>
<P>
This South American country, having suffered an inflation rate
of 39.5 percent in 1993 and 15.4 percent in 1994, saw its consumer
price index increase by 11.9 percent. Meanwhile, the United
Nations Economic Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean
expected the average inflation for the region in 1996 would be
19.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
As for the annual evolution of prices in eight groupings of
consumption, three of them closed above the average inflation
rate. They were housing, fuel and electricity; medical and health
preservation, and transportation and communication.
</P>
<P>
Under agreements reached with the International Monetary Fund,
Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori should keep the inflation rate
between 10.5 and 11.5 percent in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
