<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai PM Reiterates Promise of 2-Year Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh has reiterated his promise to stay in office for no
more than two years, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
During his campaign for the general elections on November 17
last year, Chavalit, leader of the New Aspiration Party, had said
that if he became prime minister, he would leave office after the
adoption of a new constitution. The process of drafting and
approval of a new constitution is expected to take about two
years.
</P>
<P>
A 99-member constitution drafting assembly, elected in late
December 1996, is responsible for making a draft within eight
months.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit reiterated his promise of the two-year term on the New
Year's day when he called on Luang Phor Koon, a distinguished monk
in Thailand who is now in hospital.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, the monk said that he wished Chavalit
could complete the four-year term as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"I think two years are enough. I made a promise ...... I must
keep my word," Chavalit replied.  
</P>
</TEXT>
