<HEADLINE> Foreign Funds Boost Gansu's Telecom Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Gansu
Province has channelled foreign loans and investment of more than
90 million US dollars to its telecommunications industry,
digitalizing all its telephone systems over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
According to the Beijing-based "People's Posts and
Telecommunications News," the landlocked province launched a
number of large-scale telecom projects, including a 200,000-line
telephone switching system supported by loans from Australia, and
a Spain-funded digital microwave trunk which connects six cities
together.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a World Bank loan was spent on a optical cable line
between the provincial capital of Lanzhou and Beijing, and several
satellite ground stations.
</P>
<P>
The Australian loan was also used to build a 3,000-km optical
cable line connecting Lanzhou, Xining and Urumqi, capital of the
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the fixed assets of Gansu's telecom
industry now stand at 3.2 billion yuan, compared with the 500
million yuan in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
