<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Swiss President Expects 1997 Year of Renewal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Swiss President Arnold Koller
expects 1997 to be a year of renewal, he said in the Swiss capital
of Bern today when taking over the presidency of the confederation
for 1997 from his predecessor Jean-Pascal Delamuraz.
</P>
<P>
In his short inaugural speech, Koller mentioned certain
concerns shadowed by little growth of population and economy
growth in six years and much more fierce international
competition.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Koller reminded the Swiss people that their
country was in a situation much better than most of other
countries in the world. He underlined Switzerland's strong points
including well-trained personnel, political stability and high
productivity.
</P>
<P>
Koller, also minister of justice and police, appealed for
responsibilities of economic leaders among a crisis traversing the
Swiss society. He said that international competition should not
destroy the values of human dignity and social justice.
</P>
<P>
Koller expressed his hope that supporters of the
open-to-the-world policy and defenders of Switzerland's traditions
will stop their disputes in the new year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
